BUD BREAK.
Bud break, as its known in the biz, is the first stage of the vine cycle that yields grapes each fall. As the name suggests (though bud burst may be more appropriate), new green growth appears on the vines during this stage. Magically, entire regions go from brown and drab to green and vibrant during a few weeks each spring. The process is not only beautiful, but sets the stage for a productive season and puts hundreds of vineyard workers back in the fields.

=====================================
The City of Los Angeles holds many distinctions. L.A. is the entertainment capital of the world, a cultural mecca boasting more than 100 museums, many of them world-class, and a paradise of idyllic weather. From tourist attractions like the Walk of Fame‚Äôs collection of stars (numbering more than 2,614 and growing by one or two a month) to career opportunities like those presented in the expanding tech industry, Los Angeles is the place to be. It is the only city in North America to have hosted the Summer Olympics twice - and by 2028 the third time. Downtown L.A. is the largest government center outside of Washington, D.C. Los Angeles has the only remaining wooden lighthouse in the state (located in San Pedro‚Äôs Fermin Park) and the largest historical theater district on the National Register of Historic Places (located Downtown on Broadway).
Los Angeles is on the leading edge of several growth industries. The Los Angeles metropolitan area, with more than 23,000 art jobs, is the country's leading artistic center, surpassing the previous champion, New York. In other words, Los Angeles has both a larger concentration and absolute number of artists than New York. The L.A. five-county area is also a major tech center, with more than 700,000 people at work in health services/biomedical activities and 190,000 people in aerospace.(¬©Ô∏èwww.discoverlosangeles.com)

ATLANTA...I spent 7 years living in this city. 
True Story -> When I moved from Houston to ATL, I didn‚Äôt really know anyone. I journeyed to this new city having to figure it all out a week from my 24th Birthday relying solely on God and my faith. I‚Äôve always been brave and never really scared to try new things or venture out into the unknown. I was a young woman in a new city, had no friends, and had no family there. I was forced to step out of my comfort zone, grow, and figure it out. That step of faith and 7yr journey made me so much stronger. It was a step of faith for me. I‚Äôm a big believer of stepping out on faith and just going for it when it all doesn‚Äôt necessarily make sense. It‚Äôs been my life story! Jumping out of the airplane with no parachute on and letting God do the rest. 
True Story -> When I moved to LA, I had no job or a place to stay...But GOD met my needs the moment I left ATL while I was actually driving on my way to LA. I stepped out of the boat, trusted God, and he showed up. *It‚Äôs amazing what can happen when you have faith and trust HIM. I‚Äôm not sure who my short story of stepping out on faith or just simply trusting God can help, but during this time when things may be uncertain and no one knows what the future holds, hold on to your faith and cling to God. The Bible says, "Do not be anxious about anything, but in every situation, by prayer and petition, with thanksgiving, present your requests to God. And the peace of God, which transcends all understanding, will guard your hearts and your minds in Christ Jesus." Know that God is in control, and have faith knowing that he will supply all of your needs. He‚Äôs always been there, and he has never left us and he never will. Trust God when it doesn‚Äôt make sense!! #BeBlessed

insta_description:
Photos taken a few days ago before all this quarantine started. 
All everyone is talking about is this virus. 
Its wild. 
I dont need to remind anyone to wash their hands or "social distance." But I will say this. 
Take care of yourself. 
For some of us, especially creative types, we are so used to going 100mph nonstop. Now that everything is forced to come to a screeching halt, many of us are losing it. Getting antsy, uncomfortable, fidgety, possibly lost in dark thoughts, neglected emotions, etc. 
Take this time to meditate. Realign with every fiber of your being. Find your peace. 
You'll still be able to create. Just focus on healing yourself during this time, give your energy an opportunity to reset.
Your ability to make art will still be there. 
The demand for your art will still be there. 
And remember that others are also going through a flurry of emotions during this time. Reach out to friends and family. Ask and see if they're doing okay. Offer to talk with them over the phone or video chat. 
Our technology gives us the ability to stay connected even when we're feeling scared/anxious/angry and alone.

insta_description:
Had a relaxing couple of days sleeping in a real bed and taking hot showers at my leisure at an Airbnb (the pink house on the right in pic) in Ocean Beach, CA over the weekend! It was amazing to get my toes in the sand and eat some yummy food! Aleister and I walked so much which was good for our sedentary bones and muscles...but, wow those hills!! The California coastline is always an awesome sight! We even got to see some seals catching a few rays... or zzzs haha! The wildflowers were beautiful and I cried at all of the GREEN everywhere!! The absolute BEST part, though, was seeing my friend and mermaid @azulnomadart who I met in Costa Rica 4 years ago! She was the first person I met when I dropped into a little beach town there...selling her art at the farmer's market and I bought a piece and we just talked and talked and I hung out with her several more times throughout the week!! It was such a fun time!  So, because I stalk her Instagram lol, I knew she lived in OB and I reached out to say hi!! What a beautiful person doing good things in this world. I'm so happy to know her!! ü§ô

insta_description:
So many mixed emotions. First, thank you to our loyal customers for calling and trying to go through us for even things by appointment. We cannot in the good of public health accommodate even touch-less service at this time. I had not been to the shop in over a week & self quarantined early in my apartment knowing I was at greater risk for my frequent use of public transit. I cannot risk my partner in Echo Park's safety, or even young employees to not be asymptomatic and spreading the virus. It is our moral obligation to stay home right now.
I'm disgusted by vendors asking us to petition local governments & our customers to call bike shops essential services right now. For the next two weeks minimum THEY ARE NOT. We need to recognize & learn from what is happening in other countries. The goal is to not overwhelm the medical system & create a mass casualty event. You can feel well & the next day have difficulty breathing. 
So we're still closed. 
We are not rich. We are taking it in the teeth like the rest of our community & scrambling to see what government aid we are eligible. Thank you to people suggesting some sort of fundraising platforms, but save your money right now for food & actual essentials. This can go on for months. We refuse to profit from scared people or the ones in denial of the gravity of the situation. Stay home and relax. Protect your immunity. ‚ù§ 
Brent built everything in the bike shop by hand & we've created this space in response to everything we wanted but didn't see in the 20+ & 30+ years (respectively) in this industry. We remain steadfast to our mission of challenging the status quo & doing right by our community.
Now, if our business fails, this has been the realization of a long held dream by two angry little bike messengers, that did not like the majority of their employers. üòÇ Revenge Fantasy realized. üòÇ It's been an AMAZING 5 year ride in this space. None of us knows what the future holds, and with any luck we'll be here long after this passes. ‚ù§
Thank you, be well, & #staythefuckhome #revengefantasycycles #resist #challengethestatusquo

I‚Äôve found this time to be two things:

1. Fucking (used as adjective here to express ultimate crazy town ness) scary.

2. Incredibly inspiring. 
Most of us can get on board with number one, but may cringe at me saying this time is inspiring. Hear me out! There is such an opportunity for us to CONNECT - with ourselves and with each other. We in these upcoming and unknown territory of days, weeks (who knows-months) get to determine what matters most to us. What do we do with our time? Do we spend more energy destroying potential or creating with it?  How much space do we allot for negative thinking and thought patterns? Who do we give our presence (in person, or even if just virtual) to (but truly, please practice safe #socialdistancing ) ? 
This is our time to get clear. To polish our hearts and not only be AWARE of what‚Äôs going on, but take the necessary actions small and large scale within ourselves, our communities, our nation, and our globe. 
It‚Äôs been the sweetest thing to have you practicing with me virtually as I share these audio files with you. üí´NEW 60 MINUTE YIN PRACTICE AVAILABLE NOW üí´ (just shoot me a DM with your email to get the file). It‚Äôs an honor to serve you and I‚Äôm humbled to have you put your time and trust of practice with me. insta_description:
ARE YOU PANICKING?

I am working hard not to. Reminding myself to have faith, to worry less and to push away negative thoughts.

Still. It's tough to ignore the endless stream of bad news. Markets crashing, schools closing, people getting sick‚Äîworry everywhere.

This is a time to pause and think about the big picture.

Why? Because people who know how to look at the big picture succeed best in life. If we give in to the stress-of-the-moment, the immediate, the right-now, we are bound to live a stressful existence. If we are able to look beyond the horizon, we can march forward.

Here is the big picture: We live in a wonderful world, and G‚Äëd has been so good to us. All of us.

Yes. The cup is not full. But it's not exactly empty, mind you. In fact, I believe it's 90% full. Maybe even more.

Like millions of Americans around me, I decided to become an expert on the Coronavirus. So I did what all experts do: I Googled.

My first stop was to read about the plague that struck the world just about 100 years ago: the Spanish Flu, which had a devastating impact on life expectancy. Before the pandemic, life expectancy in the US was about 52 years old. Due to the flu, the numbers dropped to about 39 years old.

Stop and think about it.

Right now, the entire globe is doing all they can to save older people and people with pre-condition. This is why we put entire cities in quarantine.

But 100 years ago, we barely had any 70 years old to worry about!

Then think about the people in quarantine.

100 years ago, they were isolated, alone, their families worrying constantly, they had very few options to receive information from their loved ones... And now? Facetime, Whatsapp, phone calls, text messages. Yes, quarantine is still lonely, but much less so than a century ago.

Think about the major advancements in medicine. Think about the ability to get help fast to those who need it.

Yes‚Äî the Coronavirus is something we should take seriously.

But at the same time, let's not forget about the big picture. Let's be full of gratitude to the One above for giving us such a wonderful life üôè

Credit: Mendy Kaminker of Chabad.org

insta_description:
‚ÄúThis too shall pass.‚Äù
-
-
 A few thoughts on current events:
-
-
-We will all be affected in some way because of the recent chain of events. Some of us are overreacting and helping to fuel panic. On the other hand, some of us are downplaying COVID-19, comparing it to the seasonal flu. Like any comparison, there are similarities and differences. The bottom line is, any of us could lose a loved one or a job due to COVID-19. This pandemic is a big deal for all of us precisely because it is a big deal for some of us. We‚Äôre all in this together and the more of us who do our part and take necessary precautions while staying calm, the more potential lives will be spared and sooner people can get back to work. It can be difficult to see the exact impact each one of us potentially has. As the quote goes: ‚ÄúThe single raindrop never feels responsible for the flood.‚Äù On the flip side as JFK said, ‚ÄúOne person can make a difference, and everyone should try.‚Äù -
-
-This appears to be the bear market that has been expected the last few years. Expect a rocky road for at least the next few weeks. Nobody knows what‚Äôs right around the corner. My personal opinion about trying to time the markets is this (this is what I tell myself): If you sold before the big drop (greater than a month ago), nice work (I did not). If you did not, it‚Äôs likely that for most people, the best option is to stay the course (if your time horizon is long enough). Having the foresight to get off the bus before it starts moving is great, but it‚Äôs moving pretty fast now (up and down), and it‚Äôs difficult to decide exactly when to exit and when to re-enter. It is likely that the markets will continue to decrease for at least a few weeks to a few months. Remember, you don‚Äôt really lose (or gain) money in the markets until you sell. I found looking at the recessions of ~2001 and ~2008 through an investment graph to be helpful. This won‚Äôt last forever.
-
-
Let's be the pillars that hold each other up and move us all forward.

In light of today's announcement from the Napa County Health Officer we are temporarily closing and plan on reopening on April 8th.

Our front office will be available through Friday if you would like to call or email to reschedule any bookings for the week we reopen.

We are saddened by this turn of events and want you to know we will be here for you when the corner is turned and ready to support you any way we can.

In the meantime, please take care of yourself and your loved ones. Stay hydrated. Eat healthy foods. Read those books that you have been too busy to read. Meditate or if you have it, ask Alexa to turn on the ocean sounds - Close your eyes and imagine the joy of being at the beach. 
Think positive thoughts. Call your friends especially those who live alone to let them know you are thinking of them. Skype. Face Time. Reach out. Dear Guests and Community,
We hope that everyone is remaining safe during this time of uncertainty caused by COVID-19. Your health and happiness are important to us. At this time, we will remain open for guests who are visiting the park. The two restaurants located onsite are currently offering takeout and room delivery options for guests. Our gift store and convenience store will also remain open. A few important updates are provided below. If you have any other questions or concerns, please let us know. 
As of March 17th, 2020 Yosemite National Park‚Äôs entrances, hiking trails, and the outdoor spaces around the Yosemite Village will remain open. In Yosemite Valley, the Village Store and Curry Village Gift & Grocery will remain open, along with the El Portal Market and the Wawona Store. Gas stations located at Crane Flat, Wawona, and El Portal remain open. Park visitors are asked to purchase their park passes online.

If you have an existing reservation and are unable to make it due to travel restrictions, please contact the platform with whom you made your reservation as they will be able to assist you with changes. If you made the reservation directly through us, we are happy to assist you. If you made it through a different platform such as Expedia, you will need to contact them.

We are taking extra precautions to ensure you are within a safe and healthy environment based on guidelines from the CDC. Please view the information and links below for details.

The park visitor centers, the Yosemite Valley Theater, the Yosemite Museum, along with all restaurants and lodges inside the park are closed.

Please note: The NPS urges visitors to do their part when visiting a park and to follow CDC guidance to prevent the spread of infectious diseases. More can be found at www.nps.gov/coronavirus #yosemite #california #nature #yosemiteviewlodge

accessibility_caption: Image may contain: text
insta_description:
Mortgage News Alert by the Federal Housing Finance Agency (FHFA)!! The HUD (Housing Urban Development) also announced it! .
.
.
.

What does this mean?? .
.
.
This means that homeowners who have loans that fall in the following category: FHA, VA, and Conventional Conforming Loan (e.g., 3% down, 5% , or loan amount los no greater than $510,400 in most counties and no greater than $765,600 in high costs areas) and are facing foreclosures or potentially evictions, can have the foreclosure or eviction process suspended/temporarily stopped for at least 60 days due to the coronavirus national emergency. In other words, if you are currently defaulted on your home loan (missed payments) and your home is about to be sold or foreclosed on, then the government is temporarily suspending foreclosure for at least 60 days. .
.
.
In addition, the federal government is allowing payment forbearance to borrowers impacted by the coronavirus. Forbearance in short allows the lender to freeze your payments for a set amount of time in this case up to 12 months. This mechanism is identical to forbearing your student loans until graduations or acquiring a job to pay for the student loans or other exceptional factor. .
.
.
Make sure you contact a lender, mortgage broker or a licensed attorney in the given state jurisdiction on how this order may apply to you and seeing if you can request for a forbearance with your mortgage servicer. A mortgage servicing company is a company that you as a consumer are making mortgage payments to. Usually, a Mortgage servicer is the one that sends you monthly mortgage statements in the mail or electronically. .
.
.

insta_description:
And then. I headed down the freeway and knew this wasn't a good sign. At the time I thought, this will be funny...I can caption the Corona Fwy Sign pic with something witty, like "I probably shouldn't go this way!" Well, the joke was on me, for sure!

I was heading north on I15 going toward Barstow, then to SR247 south...BUT, there was a shorter route that had me just cut across to get to my destination. I mean, it was on Google maps, so had to be a road, right? It was. Dirt all the way.

45 minutes into it, knowing full well this wasn't going to end well (I usually ALWAYS trust my intuition,  but it was getting late and I wanted to get where I was going...had no idea there was a mountain right in the middle) I ended up stuck trying to drive up a too-steep, rocky dirt road. When I realized we weren't going to make it up, I tried to back down and the trailer jack-kniffed and my front driver side tire started spinning. I unhitched my camper to try and help, but it only rolled down the hill and got itself stuck. Fortunately something stopped it from going far (btw, I was holding onto it the entire time)! Anyway, it all worked out ok. Roadside assistance sent a 4x4 out to get me (not covered, btw) and I was on my way back the way I came about 3 hours later (2 of those were me trying to do it myself). It was full dark and 37 degrees when they got there! Spent the night curled up with Aleister in the backseat at a truck stop. 
It's taken me a couple of days to even process my unpreparedness for that event. I had zero cell service the whole way in until that very spot where I got stuck. I did have plenty of water, food, warm clothing and blankets... Resting and recuperating for a minute then, onward! üëä

insta_description:
Three Reasons Why This Is Not a Housing Crisis
.
1. The Market Today Is Vastly Different from 2008
.
We all remember 2008. Today‚Äôs market conditions are far from the time when housing was a key factor that triggered a recession. From easy-to-access mortgages to skyrocketing home price appreciation, a surplus of inventory, excessive equity-tapping, and more ‚Äì we‚Äôre not where we were in 2008. None of those factors are in play today. Rest assured, housing is not a catalyst that could spiral us back to that time or place. In addition, the Goldman Sachs GDP Forecast released this week indicates that although there is no growth anticipated immediately, gains are forecasted heading into the second half of this year and getting even stronger in early 2021 (see graph above).
.
2. A Recession Does Not Equal a Housing Crisis
.
Next, take a look at the past five recessions in U.S. history. Home values actually appreciated in three of them. It is true that they sank by almost 20% during the last recession, but as we‚Äôve identified above, 2008 presented different circumstances. In the four previous recessions, home values depreciated only once (by less than 2%). In the other three, residential real estate values increased by 3.5%, 6.1%, and 6.6% (see graph above).
.
3. We Can Be Confident About What We Know
.
Concerns about the impact COVID-19 will have on the economy are real. And they‚Äôre scary, as the health and wellness of our friends, families, and loved ones are high on everyone‚Äôs radar. That said, we can be confident that, while we don‚Äôt know the exact impact the virus will have on the housing market, we do know that housing isn‚Äôt the driver. The reasons we move ‚Äì marriage, children, job changes, retirement, etc. ‚Äì are parts of life. As noted in the New York Times, ‚ÄúEveryone needs someplace to live.‚Äù
.
Concerns about a recession are real, but housing isn‚Äôt the driver. If you have questions about what it means for your family‚Äôs homebuying or selling plans, let‚Äôs connect to discuss your needs!
.
.

-
The only thing that will spread faster then this virus is greed, negativity and selfishness. Supporting one another will however make us stronger. insta_description:
CHANGE
I don‚Äôt think anyone really likes change, I know I don‚Äôt! Even if it‚Äôs for something better or for something that I want, I always face it with resistance (I blame it on my double Taurus). There‚Äôs a lot of newness in my life right now, most of it is for the good of my community, and that we all are experiencing, and the other is something that I‚Äôve prayed for and thought into existence. All this change happened at the exact same time! And for someone who haaatteeess change I‚Äôve been having a really hard time coping with it.
My own personal change is something I‚Äôve wanted for a really long time and it‚Äôs something amazing! But a huge part of me feels like I don‚Äôt deserve it. For all of my life I thought to myself ‚ÄúI‚Äôm just one of those people who has to work harder for the things I want in life‚Äù, and this year I‚Äôve been trying to change that narrative to ‚Äúwork smarter not harder‚Äù and once I got a glimmer of what that looks like I ran back to ‚Äúit shouldn‚Äôt be this easy‚Äù, ‚ÄúI need to work hard.‚Äù And I‚Äôve sat with this feeling and thought on it and it all comes back to that I don‚Äôt believe I deserve it, that for some reason somewhere in my life I thought life had to be hard in order for me to feel successful or to feel deserving. I‚Äôm scared of change, I‚Äôm scared of change because there‚Äôs comfort in old habits, there‚Äôs comfort in old thinking and in the things I know but are no longer serving me. I‚Äôm working on letting the universe guide me and having full faith in it and myself. Change is scary, but we got this.
